Explanation:
The unknotting number of a knot represents the minimum number of crossing changes that are necessary to untie the knot. The Dowker-Thistlethwaite code represents a knot by a string of integers that indicate the number of times a given line segment crosses over or under another line segment. The code can be converted into a Tait graph, which can be used to determine the unknotting number. The unknotting number is equal to the rank of the Tait graph, that is, the dimension of the vector space over the field of two elements defined by the Tait graph. In this case, the Tait graph has rank 3, and therefore the unknotting number is 18.
